posts.description:
Bologna, and just some of its 40km of medieval porticos 💚🇮🇹👏 (arched covered walkways) Most of the walkways in this ancient city have them, making it very easy to stroll around and stay dry in wet weather, and keep shaded from the sun in summer ⛅ And did you also know that Bologna has the oldest university in Europe 📝🎓 And that concludes today's lesson on Bologna 😊 I love a good fact! Does anyone else have any juicy facts about other Italian cities they can share? 👂

Florence, you are something else entirely 💙🇮🇹⛲ The extraordinary view from Piazza Michelangelo up on the hill, on the south bank of the Arno River 🌼 We did a day trip from Bologna over the Easter weekend, only a half hour fast train away 👏 Has anyone else been up that hill for sunset? 😍

Bird's-eye view of Bologna, looking down from the Asinelli Tower 🇮🇹🗼 That other smaller tower leans even more than Pisa (😱) thanks to the the sandstone ground found in the Emilia-Romagna region 😰 Great for growing produce, not so great for building tall towers 😅 Despite this, between the 12th and 13th century, the number of towers in the city was around 180. Now there's only about 20. They're thought to have been built by wealthy families as a public display of wealth. The taller your tower, the more 💰 you had.

Bologna eats: affettati misti e formaggi, mixed cold cuts and local cheeses 🇮🇹😋💚 Mortadella, salumi, Parmigiano Reggiano, Crescenta (a thin, 4-inch round bread), Prosciutto di Parma, mostarda Bolognese (jam made of quince and plums), other tasty bits, and a chilled glass of local Lambrusco 🍷👌 Easy to see why the Emilia-Romagna region is known as the pantry of Italy 🍅🍒🍇

Scenes from Bologna, Italy 🇮🇹🍝💚🙏 I've noticed all the pics I've taken here have a beautiful rust hue, thanks to the terracotta colour of the buildings and rooftops, earning the city the nickname of "La Rossa”, The Red 🎈 I highly approve. Lots of Instagram Stories from exploring the city yesterday. Today we're popping over to Florence, as it's only half an hour train ride away 🍅 Stay tuned 👍

Got @pasta 🍝🇮🇹👌 Back in Italy again after last week - can't stay away 🙏 In Bologna for the long Easter weekend - the ancient capital of the Emilia-Romagna region - and home to many Italian food staples we all know and love. I headed out of the city today with lovely Max from @amazingitalytourswithus, visiting a Parmegiano Reggiano production site, checking out how Prosciutto di Modena is made, and sampling traditional balsamic vinegar of Modena, aged for 30 years 😍 Splurged on a bottle too, and a big hunk of 36 month old cheese for home 💙 Also visited Maranello, the home of Ferrari 🚗💨💨 Learnt heaps - check out my Instagram Stories for the behind the scenes.
➖
This snap taken in Catania, Sicily last week - the fab home-cooked Sicilian meal we made in our @homeawayuk property 😌 #OntheTable: pasta con le sarde (sardine pasta), caponata (a sort of aubergine stew), steamed artichokes, blood orange and fennel salad, whole roasted onions, salami, and some Mount Etna wine 🌋🍷👌 Have a fab Easter everyone 🐣

Listen up friends: some of the best Turkish food I've had in London can be found @skewdkitchen. LOOK at this beautiful spread 🇹🇷💙 They have one guy whose job it is just to bake the bread (6 different types 😍), their fish is from Billingsgate, they have the same meat supplier as Hawksmoor, they make absolutely everything from scratch (except the ice cream - I'll let that slide 😅), and Exec Chef Maz recently won 'Chef of the Year' at the British Kebab Awards. Continuing with my #BeyondZone1 series, this place might be in Cockfosters (last stop on the Piccadilly line, for realz 😱), but it is categorically a must visit if you like Turkish food.
➖
#OnTheTable: Mixed pide; mini lahmacun; mixed kebab; hellim with smoked mushrooms 🍄 hummus with diced lamb; pistachio and honey-crusted lamb chops; lamb's liver with parsley and cumin 👅 bullet chillies; pachanga (filo pastry filled with mixed bell peppers, chestnut mushrooms); awesome salad with figs, sultanas, dates, cranberries, apple, tulum cheese, walnuts, sumac and pomegranate molasses; Ocean kebab with wild Alaskan salmon, monkfish, octopus and king prawns 🐙, an assortment of mezze dips, and gallons of çay 👍 Already plotting my next visit #ThisIsLondon #sp #EaterLondon

The neighbourhood lanes and street urchins of Catania, Sicily 🇮🇹👧👦💙
